\begin_layout Standard
Pacman is the Arch Linux
\series bold
 pac
\series default
kage 
\series bold
man
\series default
ager.
 This underpins Pamac and Octopi but doesn't have a graphical interface.
 Instead, it is used by typing commands on the terminal.
 The commands allow you to install, upgrade, configure, and remove software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Синхронизация с репозиториями Manjaro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As new packages are added to the repositories you will need to regularly
 synchronise the package lists.
 This is normally taken care of automatically on a regular basis by the
 software managers, but to perform this manually type the following into
 the terminal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Sy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will only download the package lists if there has been a change.
 Occasionally you may want to force the package lists to be downloaded.
 To do this, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Обновление программ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pacman will allow you to perform an update of software already installed
 with the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Su
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's a good idea to check whether the package lists are up-to-date at the
 same time.
 To do so, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can also force a package list synchronisation before performing an update
 with:
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/welcome-to-manjaro/pacman/pacman-syyu.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 95col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syyu
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syyu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Поиск программного обеспечения
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding a package by name is really straightforward.
 For example, to search for a text editor called Leafpad, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Ss leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Установка программного обеспечения
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Installing a package is equally straightforward.
 For example, to install Leafpad, type:
\begin_inset Flex Marginnote
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Many software applications depend on other software packages.
 Thankfully, Pacman will automatically detect and install these!
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -S leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Удаление программ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To remove a software package you need to know its name, but the command
 is straightforward.
 To remove Leafpad, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -R leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's also possible to remove a package and any dependencies it required
 when it was installed.
 Assuming those other packages are not being used by another piece of software,
 they will become
\series bold
 orphan
\series default
 packages.
 These serve no function other than taking up space! To remove a software
 package with its dependencies, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rs leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A package may also create configuration files.
 Normally these are left in place so your configuration is not lost, and
 can be reused if you install the package again.
 However, if you want to remove these configuration files too, the command
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rns leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If at a later date you want to remove all orphan packages and configuration
 files for packages that you removed some time ago, the following command
 will do it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rns $(pacman -Qtdq)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be warned, though: this is an advanced command!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Прочие команды Pacman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's a good idea to become familiar with the Pacman commands.
 It can be a very useful tool in case the other software managers refuse
 to complete an installation, for example if an installation process is
 interrupted.
 The Pacman man
