\begin_layout Subsection
Переключение ветвей
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Switching branches
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Branches
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you install Manjaro, unless you specifically installed a preview version,
 you will be using the stable branch.
 This set of packages has the most testing and so is the best for most users.
 However, you may want to help test packages before they move to the stable
 repository.
 To do this, you can switch to the testing branch with the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman-mirrors -f -a -B testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The testing repository has packages that have been checked by the Manjaro
 development team to make sure they work correctly.
 However, the amount of testing done is much smaller than for the stable
 branch - but this is how they get tested!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you want to live on the bleeding edge, you can switch to the unstable
 branch.
 This is normally used by the Manjaro developers.
 Packages from the unstable branch can cause problems, so this is not something
 to do lightly.
 If you ever decide to try it out, the command is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman-mirrors -f -a -B unstable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After switching branches you will need to force an update of the package
 lists and packages, which can be done with the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syyu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you switch away from the stable branch, but want to move back, it's actually
 pretty easy.
 You can switch back to the stable branch in the same way you left it, with
 the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman-mirrors -f -a -B stable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will leave the newer packages on your system and these will be replaced
 as the stable branch catches up.
 However, if you want to force a downgrade of packages back to the stable
 version, use:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syyuu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Исправление ошибок установки
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fixing installation errors
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Occasionally, an installation can go wrong.
 The downloaded file might be corrupted, or the process might be interrupted
 if you lose power.
 Most of the time it's relatively easy to get your system back to a working
 state!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common error you will be something like:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
:: Synchronising package databases...
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to update core (unable to lock database)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to update extra (unable to lock database)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to update community (unable to lock database)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to update multilib (unable to lock database)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to synchronise any databases
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: failed to init transaction (unable to lock database)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

error: could not lock database: File exists
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

if you're sure a package manager is not already running,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

you can remove /var/lib/pacman/db.lck
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means Pacman thinks it is already running.
 If it is, and you try to force an installation or removal of software,
 the package database can be left in an inconsistent state.
 This would be bad.
 So, the first thing to check is whether an installer is running.
 One of the easiest ways to check is to run a terminal command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
ps x | grep pacman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This might look complicated, but it's just two small commands joined (piped)
 together.
 First,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
ps x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
produces a list of running processes for all users.
 Second,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
grep pacman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
searches for the text 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pacman
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The pipe, |, takes the output from the first and feeds it to the second.
 To check whether another program is running you can just change the text
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pacman
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to something else:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
ps x | grep pamac
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
ps x | grep octopi
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you are sure an installer is not running, you can delete Pacman's lock
 file with the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo rm /var/lib/pacman/db.lck
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then try running the install process again!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a problem persists, there is a series of commands that will fix most
 issues:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo rm -f /var/lib/pacman/db.lck
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

sudo pacman-mirrors -g
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

sudo pacman -Syyuu
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

sudo pacman -Suu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order, these commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Remove Pacman's lock file;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Update the mirror list;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Forces an update of the package lists and an update of any packages to bring
 them in line with the current repository state;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ensures no packages are left out of line with the current repository state.
\end_layout

